  "raw_tex_source": "\n\\maketitle\n\n\\section{Introduction}\n[[SOURCE:examples\\sample_tex_project\\sections\\introduction.tex]]\nThis paper studies a compact auditing pipeline for academic prose. It is important to note that the proposed approach provides a robust framework for rapidly inspecting suspicious language in a paper.\n\nWe focus on sentence-level evidence so that a reviewer can read the source material without trusting a single global detector score. The results demonstrate that local evidence is easier to inspect than a single document-wide label.\n\n\n\\section{Methods}\n[[SOURCE:examples\\sample_tex_project\\sections\\methods.tex]]\nOur workflow indexes a local corpus and compares each sentence against previously written literature. The proposed pipeline computes lexical overlap, phrase overlap, and vector similarity against candidate source passages.\n\nAdditionally, the system measures whether a sentence sounds smoother and more formulaic than its neighbors. This highlights the fact that some academic filler language is more irritating than informative.\n\n\n",
